===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|j}}: The oracle-bone form depicts a lidded {{zh-l|同|tube; cylindrical vessel}}. Some forms contain strokes inside the vessel, probably representing its contents. In Western Zhou bronze inscriptions, the {{zh-l|同}} element changed into {{zh-l|用}}. One proposal identifies this graph as the original character of {{zh-l|醓}} (“meat sauce; minced meat preserved in brine”).<ref>黄博.甲骨文“南”及相关字补说[J].出土文献,2020,(04):24-37+155.
</ref>

{{och-l|南|tr=*nˤəm}} may be related to {{och-l|腩|tr=*nˤəmʔ}} and {{och-l|納|tr=*nˤəp}} (“to put in; to receive”).

===Etymology 1===
From {{der|zh|sit-pro|*g-nam||sky, sun}} (STEDT; {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}; {{zh-ref|Benedict (1972)}}); the south is traditionally associated with the sun & light, compare {{och-l|陽|light, sun-lit south-side of a hill}}.
: If so, cognate with {{cog|bo|གནམ||sky}}, {{m|bo|ནམ||night}}, {{cog|tsj|ngam||sun, noon, day, sky}}, {{cog|cdm|न्‍याम्‌|tr=nyam|t=sun, sunlight, storm-cloud, weather}}.

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Sagart (2004)}} relates this word to Old Chinese *''nɨm'' (revised to *''nˤ[ə]m'' in 2014) "belly, front of the body", further "south" to {{cog|sit-pro|*s-nam||rib(s)}}, as one term for one body-part often shifts its meaning to another body-part nearby.
: If so, {{lang|zh|南}} is cognate with {{och-l|妊|to carry inside one's belly → to be pregnant}}, {{och-l|任|to carry a burden, especially in front of the body}}, also {{och-l|腩|belly (of an ox)}}, {{cog|pmj|nõ⁵⁵}}, {{cog|my|နံရိုး||side of the body, rib}}, and thus is a semantic counterpart to {{och-l|北|north}}, which is related to {{och-l|背|back of the body}}.

